const mapB = new Map([['b', 2], ['a', 1]]);
 
_.isEqual(mapA, mapB);
// => true
```

# Expected Behavior

The above comparison should return `false`, as JS `Map`s have an explicit contract to track insertion order and hence the two maps are not equal. (One could use the `Map` as and "ordered map", but `_.isEqual` would discard those differences and just return true).

I came across this issue with a `Map` nested deep inside another data structure, so it's not easily possible to switch to a `Map` specific comparison function on the top level.

`isEqual` treats `NaN` equal to `NaN` but this should not be the case:

```js
NaN == NaN;
// => false
NaN === NaN;
// => false
_.isEqual(NaN, NaN);
// => true
```
